               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1044" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1044" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1044" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1044" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>HENRY WILLIAM THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. William Dent and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184504070189"></xptr>
               <p>another—they are plumbers—the prisoner was in their employ—on the morning of the 4th of April, I stopped the prisoner as he was leaving the warehouse—I called him into the counting-house, and told him I suspected he had got some lead on his person—he put his hand into his pocket, and pulled out 11lbs. of lead—he said he hoped Mr. Dent would forgive him, it was his first offence—this is the lead—it is my masters'.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was the prisoner work ing at? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Cutting lead into small pieces to stow it tway—it comes to us in large pieces—he was going to breakfast when he was charged with this—he said at once he had a piece of lead—he had worked for my master about two years, and up to this time we had every confidence in him—he said he had broken his knife in cutting the lead, and took this lead to repay him.</p>
               <p>
